1 - Deadlines can help you finish the project, give yourself a date and try your best to meet that date

2 - Open the project file first thing, it can be tempting to start a new idea, but remember the deadline for the project

3 - You may want to work on something until it sounds perfect, but often times you can burn out stressing out over perfection, wait until the entire track is finished to worry about those final touches that make your sounds perfect.

4 - Sometimes it is easy to work for hours on a project without a break...but this can often lead to creativity burnout and stress...be sure to take breaks every now and then.

5 - This may be the most important...fun is often the fuel to a musicians creative engine, have fun!

Make your music sound even better with correct monitor placement.

Ensure your tweeters are at ear level.

Create a triangle, placing your monitors at a slight angle facing your head.

Make sure your monitors are far away from any walls.

Try to sit as close to the center line of your room as possible. (Not too close to the left or right walls)

You finished an awesome track, so how do you mix it?

Its normally best to start at the loudest section of your track.

Leave enough headroom for mastering. ~ (-6db)

Make this section impactful, dynamic, and the right volume first.

Then move on to the quiet parts.

This can help you have a consistent volume and dynamics throughout the track.

And can save time by not needing to re-mix the song if the loudest section ends up being too loud.

You are creative with the music.

You can also be creative with how you use your DAW.

become a master of your DAW.

Just like a violinist needs to master their violin.

Learn all the things unique to your  DAW.

And be creative with them.

Free VST to check your LUFS are " MLoudnessAnalyzer " and " YouLean loudness meter " " LUFS " is a loudness measurement.

Most streaming sites have automatic loudness adjustments.

If your final track is too loud it will automatically turn it down.

If the track is too quiet it will turn it up.

This can affect the dynamics of your track.
-
So when uploading, try to make sure your track is at the right LUFS before hand.

This will ensure the website doesn't change your hard work.

When mixing.

Imagine a room in front of you.

Place the elements within the room at different depths.

Close objects should sound louder and brighter than farther objects.

Far objects should have less high end, and be less loud.

Decide what elements you want in the front and back of the room

And where you want them panned.

You make great music, not your gear.

There are plenty of people with beautiful studios, and unimpressive music.

While others only have laptop speakers and make amazing productions.

An easy way to train your ears.

Is by using filters on well mixed tracks. (Grammy awarded mixes tend to be great)

1. Find the WAV for a track that you like, that is mixed well.

2. Move your hi and low pass filters across the track.

3. Become familiar with all the instruments, and their frequency spectrum.(what frequency does the bass stop, how loud is the bass etc) - Get used to hearing how great mixes sound, and why they sound great.

Then you can use what you've learned on your own mixes.

Focus on one thing at a time.

If your snare, vocal, synth etc, isn't perfect don't worry about it.

You can fix all the elements while mixing.

If you're making room for a repetitive sound (kicks, snares, etc)

Try volume automation.

If you're making space for a dynamic sound (vocals, flutes, etc). Try sidechain compression.

If your bass sounds louder on certain notes.

Your bass may have too much dynamic range.

An easy way to fix this is by compressing and limiting the bassline.

Until all notes have the same volume.
